# Performance Standards

## Memoization — Only When Measured

Premature memoization adds complexity without benefit. Only memoize when you have a measured performance problem.

**Do memoize:**

```typescript
// Expensive sort/filter on a large list
const sorted = useMemo(
  () => [...items].sort((a, b) => b.createdAt - a.createdAt),
  [items]
);

// Stable callback passed to a React.memo child
const handleDelete = useCallback((id: string) => deleteItem(id), [deleteItem]);
```

**Do NOT memoize:**

- Simple value reads, string formatting, or boolean expressions
- Components that receive frequently-changing props anyway
- Functions that are not passed as props to children

## Long Lists

Use virtualization for lists with more than ~50 items:

- **Web**: `@tanstack/react-virtual` or native CSS `content-visibility: auto`
- **Mobile**: Use `FlatList` — never `ScrollView` wrapping a `map()` for dynamic data

```typescript
// Mobile — always FlatList for dynamic lists
<FlatList
  data={items}
  keyExtractor={item => item.id}
  renderItem={({ item }) => <FeatureCard item={item} />}
/>
```

## Code Splitting (Web)

Lazy-load heavy feature components that aren't on the initial route:

```typescript
import dynamic from 'next/dynamic';

const HeavyChart = dynamic(() => import('@/components/features/HeavyChart'), {
  loading: () => <LoadingState />,
  ssr: false,
});
```

## React Query Caching

- Do not set a global `staleTime` — configure per query when data changes rarely
- Do not call `refetch` manually — rely on cache invalidation after mutations
- Avoid `suspense: true` in queries unless the whole page is wrapped in a `Suspense` boundary

## State Subscription Performance

Context re-renders every consumer whenever any value in the context changes. For state that updates frequently, use Zustand with targeted selectors:

```typescript
// BAD — Context causes all consumers to re-render on any state change
const { notifications, filters, cart } = useAppContext();

// GOOD — Zustand selector: component only re-renders when notifications changes
const notifications = useNotificationStore((s) => s.notifications);
```

Each `useStore(selector)` call creates an independent subscription. Components subscribing to different slices are completely isolated from each other's updates.

## Image Optimization (Web)

Use Next.js `<Image>` instead of `<img>` for automatic resizing, lazy loading, and format optimization.
